<comment datatype='string'>The &lt;i&gt;cspB&lt;/i&gt; gene was significantly upregulated in bacterial cells associated with lettuce roots in a microarray analysis [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22830299&quot;&gt;Hou12&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
In spite of showing a match to the consensus CRP, &lt;i&gt;cspB, cspG,&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;cspI&lt;/i&gt; are regulated indirectly by CRP-cAMP during growth at 37&lt;sup&gt;o&lt;/sup&gt;C as well as 15&lt;sup&gt;o&lt;/sup&gt;C  [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25637299&quot;&gt;Uppal15&lt;/a&gt;]. It is probable that putative sites in these genes have become degenerate and have lost the binding function during the evolutionary process [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25637299&quot;&gt;Uppal15&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
The mRNA produced by the  &lt;i&gt;cspB&lt;/i&gt; gene has been observed mainly in the poles of the cell [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31540875&quot;&gt;Kannaiah19&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
The &lt;i&gt;cspB&lt;/i&gt; gene is highly expressed in long-term stationary phase (LTSP)  [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32753505&quot;&gt;Kram20&lt;/a&gt;].
</comment>
